The two shampoos, one marketed to women and the other to men, are functionally identical, both formulated to cleanse and treat all hair types. Despite their nearly indistinguishable product descriptions, the women’s version costs $13.99 and is packaged in a pastel pink, floral-designed bottle, while the men’s version is priced lower at $9.99 with neutral packaging. This price discrepancy highlights the pink tax, where nearly identical products are priced higher when targeted at women, solely based on gendered aesthetics rather than differences in quality or function.
